        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Selection of the observed frequency band and molecular lines

Here we mainly focus on the 12CO, 13CO J=3-&gt;2 lines as well as 
SiO v=1 J=8-&gt;7  maser line toward W43A. It has been confirmed 
that the 12CO J=3-&gt;2 line is one of the brightest CO transitions 
in O-rich evolved star. Simultaneous observations of 12CO and 13CO 
lines are important for the atomic abundance diagnostics and 
possible only in Band-7 (CO J=3-&gt;2). So as to cover the whole 
velocity width of the jet (~250 km/s) the center frequencies, 
namely their input central frequencies, shall be adjusted. The 
velocity resolution of 0.9 km/s (after Hanning smoothing) is 
fine enough to find the velocity structure even in the relic AGB 
CSEs with a relatively low expansion velocity (V_exp=10--20 km/s). 
The bright continuum emission (About 300--400 mJy), and other 
important molecular lines such as SiS, SO, SO2, H13CN, and CH3CN 
will be observed in two 1.875 GHz base bands within a nominal 
data output rate.  

Sensitivity
On-source integration time is set to approximately 15 min in 
order to yield 1-sigma noise sensitivity of apprximately 5 mJy. 
The W43A circumstellar envelope may have a 12CO flux density of 
about 1 Jy. This is conservative assumption, much lower than the 
detection limit of the previous CO observation (Imai et al. 2009) 
and the flux density of the CO emission toward IRAS 16342-3814 
with a similar source distance (Figure 3) (Imai et al. 2012). The 
requested sensitivity is determined in order to map much fainter 
CO emission from the bipolar jet (about 50 mJy) and SiO v=1 J=8-&gt;7 
maser emission (about 200 mJy) over 10-sigma and 40-sigma noise 
levels, respectively. The morphological model of the water maser 
region (Chong et al. 2014) predicts that a wide-angle bipolar jet 
should form bipolar caps of condensed molecular gas where the 
water maser emission is excited to form the observed bow-shock 
pattern. We expect the SiO J=8-&gt;7 maser to be as bright as or 
slightly fainter than the SiO J=1-&gt;0 maser in W43A (about 500 mJy)
(Imai et al. 2005). The S/N ratio of 40 yields a relative position 
accuracy better than 0".002, good enough to resolve the velocity 
structure in the vicinity of the central system (Figure 1). 

Imaging
The imaging feasibility is demonstrated in Figure 6. It is 
convincing that the angular size of the W43A system is smaller than 
2".0 (Lagadec et al. 2011) and all emission from W43A is captured 
in the most extended array configuration. The yielded angular 
resolution (0".15) and sensitivity can resolve the blue-shifted and 
red-shifted lobes of the jet, including the molecular caps and the 
jet itself at the upper stream. The direction of the upper stream 
will be compared with the location of the SiO maser emission and 
the major axis of the water maser jet to explore the binarity of 
the W43A system.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
