    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>"Water fountain" (WF) sources represent a short phase of transition from a 
spherical AGB into non-spherical post-AGB star. The main feature of the 
WF is the existence of a collimated, fast bipolar jet traced by H2O masers. 
Here we propose imaging of molecular line and continuum emission in ALMA 
Cycle-2 observations at Band-7 toward the archetypical WF W43A. VLBI 
observations of the masers (H2O, SiO, OH) spatially resolve the bow-shock 
structure in the jet, the equatorial flow in the vicinity of the star, and 
slow expansion of the spherical envelope on the mas-scale. The ALMA imaging 
can resolve the W43A system into these kinematical components spatially and 
spectroscopically. Observations of the continuum emission suggest that the 
envelope has been just sculptured and photoionization of the envelope by the 
star has just started. These results predict the rapid evolution of W43A on 
the decades scale and strongly recommend the first epoch ALMA observation to 
trace the early stage of the rapid evolution. W43A is also the most promising 
source for exploring the velocity field (torus rotation) in the very vicinity 
(~20 AU) of the central system through sub-mm SiO masers. </prp:abstract>
